Notes: L littoralis and L tenera in on our list of possible species to add; Unclear whether its Leptasterias littoralis, Leptasterias tenera, or both. Both are VERY rare now it seems, have never seen this or heard of it here. Feed in similar way (trapping small prey with tube feet). Menge papers from the 80s mention L tenera  as being part of the intertidal predator guild in the region but this is mostly thought to be a soft substrate subtidal species, whereas L littoalis is found in rocky intertidal habitats, usually among Ascophyllum in sheltered areas (see OBrien, Francis Xavier. SOME ASPECTS OF THE BIOLOGY OF A BROODING STARFISH, LEPTASTERIAS LITTORALIS (STIMPSON) 1853, n.d. for comparison of the two species)
